{
    "title": "Momentum",
    "ref": "momentum",
    "contents": [
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "parts": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "The "
                },
                {
                    "type": "bold",
                    "value": "momentum"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " of a body or particle refers, roughly speaking, to the product of the body's or particle's mass and its velocity, i.e. the time-derivative of its position:"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "latex",
            "value": "\\mathbf{p} = m\\frac{d\\mathbf{x}}{dt}"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "parts": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "In Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics, one generally refers to a more general, but still related quantity, namely the "
                },
                {
                    "type": "italic",
                    "value": "conjugate momentum"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": ", where each component "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "p_i"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " corresponding to a component "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "x_i"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " of the position, is defined as the partial derivative of the Lagrange function "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "L(x, \\dot{x})"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " of the system with respect to "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "\\dot{x}"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": ":"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "latex",
            "value": "p_i = \\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial\\dot{x}}"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "parts": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "which is not always equal to the initial definition, but which in any case then follows one of the Hamilton equations of motion:"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "latex",
            "value": "\\dot{p}_i = -\\frac{\\partial H}{\\partial x_i}"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "parts": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "Somewhat similarly in quantum mechanics, the momentum is usually and initally taken alongside the position of a particle as the quantities in terms of which a system is described. It is then defined as an operator, with its components "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "p_x, p_y, p_z"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " following the canonical commutation relations:"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "latex",
            "value": "q_i p_j - p_j q_i = i\\hbar \\delta_{i, j}"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "parts": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "where "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "\\delta_{i,j}"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " is "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "1"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " if "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "i = j"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": ", and zero otherwise. In a "
                },
                {
                    "type": "ref",
                    "value": "schrodinger-representation",
                    "label": "Schrödinger representation"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": ", the components "
                },
                {
                    "type": "latex",
                    "value": "p_i"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " generally becomes partial derivative operators with respect to the corresponding spatial coordinate, multiplied by a complex factor:"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "latex",
            "value": "p_i = -i\\hbar \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x_i}"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "parts": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "As such, the momentum "
                },
                {
                    "type": "italic",
                    "value": "vector"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": " operator becomes in the same context, a gradient operator:"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "latex",
            "value": "\\mathbf{p} = -i\\hbar\\nabla = -i\\hbar\\bigg( \\hat{\\mathbf{e}}_x \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} + \\hat{\\mathbf{e}}_y \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial y} + \\hat{\\mathbf{e}}_y \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial z} \\bigg)"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "parts": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "value": "whence, incidentally, the Laplace operator in the Schrödinger equation comes, in the term that represents the particle's kinetic energy."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}